Class JpaRepository<T,K extends java.io.Serializable>

  • java.lang.Object
    • me.nunum.whereami.framework.persistence.repositories.impl.jpa.JpaRepository<T,K>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the entity type that we want to build a repository for
    K - the key type of the entity
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.AutoCloseable, java.lang.Iterable<T>, DeleteableRepository<T,K>, IterableRepository<T,K>, Repository<T,K>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AlgorithmProviderRepositoryJpa, AlgorithmRepositoryJpa, DeviceRepositoryJpa, FeedbackRepositoryJpa, FingerprintRepositoryJpa, LocalizationRepositoryJpa, LocalizationSpamRepositoryJpa, PositionRepositoryJpa, PositionSpamRepositoryJpa, PostRepositoryJpa, PredictionRepositoryJpa, ProviderRepositoryJpa, RoleRepositoryJpa, TaskRepositoryJpa, TrainingRepositoryJpa

    public abstract class JpaRepository<T,K extends java.io.Serializable>
extends java.lang.Object
implements Repository<T,K>, IterableRepository<T,K>, DeleteableRepository<T,K>, java.lang.AutoCloseable
    An utility abstract class for implementing JPA repositories.
    Author:
    nuno

    based on stackoverflow and on burtbeckwith.

    also have a look at JPA implementation patterns

      • add

        public boolean add(T entity)
        adds and commits a new entity to the persistence store

        It is controversial if the repository class should have explicit knowledge of when to start a transaction and end it as well as to know when to open a connection and close it. this is the kind of stuff that the container (e.g., web server) should handle declaratively

        the following methods open and commit a transaction: add() save() replace() remove()

        note that other methods in this class just work with the JPA unit of work and expect the container to begin/commit transactions. they are: create() update() delete()

        Specified by:
        add in interface Repository<T,K extends java.io.Serializable>
        Parameters:
        entity -
        Returns:
        the newly created persistent object

      • save

        public T save(T entity)
        Inserts or updates an entity and commits.

        note that you should reference the return value to use the persisted entity, as the original object passed as argument might be copied to a new object

        check JPA implementation patterns for a discussion on saveOrUpdate() behavior and merge()

        Specified by:
